## What is the current behavior?

Currently, wrapping utility function calls with `runInInjectionContext` is the only way to allow utility functions to use `inject`.

For example, say we want to write a simplified way to track clicks in our app (the full example is available as documentation of the `bindToInjectionContext`).

```ts
// Provide context for where the click happened via the injection context
const CLICK_AREA = new InjectionToken<string>('click-area');

// This utility function provides a simplified interface to an imaginary TrackingService. But it
// must be called inside an injection context to work. 
function trackClick(description: string) {
  const clickArea = inject(CLICK_AREA);
  const tracker = inject(TrackerService);
  tracker.trackClick({
    clickArea,
    description,
  });
}
```

To use `trackClick`, callers must ensure, that it is called inside an injection context:

```ts
@Component({ /* ... */ })
export class MyComponent {
  // âš ï¸ We create a dependency from this component to Injector, even though
  // we don't need it directly
  private readonly injector = inject(Injector);

  trackClick(description: string) {
    runInInjectionContext(this.injector, () => trackClick(description));
  }
}
```

Doing this once is fine, but having to do this for every component that wants to call the `trackClick` function is repetitive and tedious.

Alternatively, we can also replace the `inject` calls of the `trackClick` function with parameters, like so:

 ```ts
function trackClick(description: string, clickArea: string, tracker: TrackerService) {
  // ...
}
```

But now the utility function is basically useless. The caller needs to inject both the `CLICK_AREA` and the `TrackerService`. Therefore the caller now needs to know about the services and how to track clicks properly. Might as well just call the `TrackerService` directly.

## What is the new behavior?

With `bindToInjectionContext`, developers have a much simpler way of calling utility functions, that need to have access to the current injection context.

As the name implies, `bindToInjectionContext` will take a function and return a new function, that - when called - executes the target function inside the bound injection context. The injection context can be user-controlled, but falls back to the current injection context (via `inject(Injector)`).

The above example component can therefore be simplified down to:

```ts
@Component({ /* ... */ })
export class MyComponent {
  trackClick = bindToInjectionContext(trackClick);
}
```

## Does this PR introduce a breaking change?

- [ ] Yes
- [x] No


## Other information

Originally, I wanted the utility function to be called `withInjectionContext`, as it reads nicer. However, I felt like the function name needs to properly communicate that this will bind the given callback to a specific context - just like  [Function.prototype.bind()](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Function/bind). Let me know, if you have other opinions or suggestions for names!

